title: For Sale:  WW2 Mosin Nagant 9130 rifle with PU sniper scope
postcontent: This gun is just like the gun in the movie Enemy At The Gate where the Soviets were relying on Russian Snipers with this gun to counter German movements, made famous in Stalingrad.  This particular rifle is stamped 1943 and is fitted with a newer reproduction PU style scope made in Canada to match the actual scopes of the era.  This was a laborious conversion that you can avoid doing yourself by simply buying this example instead of trying to do it yourself.!  The conversion consisted of cutting off a straight bolt, welding on a turned down bolt, tapping into the receiver to attach the scope mount, cutting down the wood stock for scope mount, and more headaches not listed.  One really cool thing about this design is that one can still shoot with the iron sights for closer shots or lift your view up to the scoped view.  Awesome gun comes with converted shotgun case, leather ammo pouch, cold weather hat, rubber and steel butt plates, leather scope lens covers, canvas scope cover, bayonet, gun strap and some ammo.

Up for grabs is this very nice AR-15 pistol chambered in the powerful 300 AAC Blackout caliber.  This caliber uses ammo that is 4 times the weight of a 5.56 for superior knock-down power.  This caliber is fast becoming the caliber of choice for Navy SEALS for close quarter action.

The upper is Olympic Arms with a 11.5" , 1:9 twist, chrome moly barrel, TufForce quad rail system, A-2 flash hider, and Brownell's bolt carrier group and charging handle. The pistol tube and brace are the latest version of the SBX from Sig Sauer.  This differs from the earlier model by having a more comfortable, wide strapping system.  There is a letter from the ATF inside the box telling you how to use the brace and NOT have the ATF declare that the gun is a SBR.  Used properly, there is no need for paying the $200 tax stamp and registering it as a SBR.

I am including 3 boxes (60 rounds) of Remington 220gr ammo already loaded into two (2) 30 round magazines.  This beauty is ready to shoot!

I have well over $1600 invested in this set-up.  I am asking a very reasonable $1175 for it as described above with the ammo included.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Luminox 3604 Titanium / Tritium Navy Seal Dive Watch
postcontent:
I just received a new watch for a B-day gift (Luminox Automatic) and decided to retire my much loved Luminox 3604. I have had this a few years, (bought new). I can never live without a Tritium illuminated watch again after this. No buttons to push to light it and it is always bright at night or dim light. It has always been very accurate and as of the first of April it has a new Lithium Energizer battery that is rated at 10 years of life in this particular watch movement. Anyone that knows watches knows that Luminox makes good stuff. If you are tired of Timex's and want a high end watch at a fraction of new price, this may be for you. 

The watch shows normal wear (I wear my watches 24/7 365 they are working machines). There are some very small blemishes in the titanium case and it has a small chip in the Sapphire Crystal at the very bottom of the 6 oclock position. I debated having a new crystal installed ( they are about $20) but it doesnt interfere with anything so I just left it alone. I still have the box (somewhere), papers and the titanium band with all links . This watch was over $600 when I purchased it new. 

Here are the factory specs. 
Microtec brand Tritium Gas Illumination Vials Throughout 
developed for the Navy SEAL's 
titanium 43 mm case with crown protector 
screw in case back and screw down crown 
water resistant to 20 atm/200 meters/660 feet 
unidirectional ratcheting bezel features bright Luminox Light Technology (LLT) "dot" encased in aluminum housing
 protected by sapphire glass window 
highly scratch resistant sapphire glass crystal with double anti-reflective coatings 
multi-jewel Swiss quartz movement with date function and 10 year lithium battery 
solid link titanium bracelet with safety clasp and extender (for use over wet suit), (lug width 22 mm) 
traser indicates dial instead of numerals
Midnight Blue Dial Face

title: For Sale:  Danish M-1867
postcontent:
Danish rifle The Model 1867 Remington rolling block rifle was the first rifle using metallic cartridges to be adopted by the Swedish and Norwegian armies. Nominally it had a caliber of 4 decimal lines, but the actual caliber was 4.1 Swedish decimal lines or 3.88 Norwegian decimal lines (12.17 mm), and it fired a rimfire round with a 12.615 mm (.497 in) lead bullet. The 12.17 mm caliber was chosen because the Swedish army had approximately 30,000 new muzzle loading Model 1860 and breech-loading Model 1864 rifles in 12.17 mm caliber in stock, rifles that were suitable for conversion to Model 1867 rolling block rifles. With the exception of the first 10,000 rifles and 20,000 actions (for conversions of older rifles), which were made by Remington in the US, all Model 1867 Remington rolling block rifles and carbines were made under license in Sweden and Norway, by Carl Gustafs stads Gevärsfaktori and Husqvarna Vapenfabriks Aktiebolag in Sweden and by Kongsberg Vaapenfabrik in Norway, with the two Swedish manufacturers producing about 80% of the weapons Birth of the M1867 In the 1860s the Swedish and Norwegian armies realized that their standard rifles, both percussion lock breech-loading rifles and muzzle loaders, were rapidly becoming obsolete in the face of the new metal cartridge combining bullet, primer and propellant load. In early October 1866, a joint Swedish-Norwegian arms commission was established in order to select a suitable cartridge and rifle for the two nations.
